  "text": "The Kubernetes service account token auto-mounting system is controlled through several interconnected components:\n\n## Admission Controller (Token Injection)\nThe admission controller at `plugin/pkg/admission/serviceaccount/admission.go` implements the ServiceAccount plugin that handles token auto-mounting for pods. The plugin implements two key decision functions:\n\n1. **shouldAutomount()** (line 254): This function determines whether a service account token should be mounted based on precedence rules:\n   - First checks pod.Spec.AutomountServiceAccountToken (Pod-level setting wins)\n   - Falls back to serviceAccount.AutomountServiceAccountToken (ServiceAccount-level setting)\n   - Defaults to true for backward compatibility\n\n2. **mountServiceAccountToken()** (line 416): When automounting is enabled, this method:\n   - Finds or generates a unique volume name with the prefix \"kube-api-access\"\n   - Adds a VolumeMount to all containers pointing to /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount\n   - Injects a projected volume containing the service account token\n\n3. **TokenVolumeSource()** (line 485): Returns a ProjectedVolumeSource containing:\n   - A ServiceAccountTokenProjection with the token at path \"token\"\n   - A ConfigMapProjection for the \"kube-root-ca.crt\" root CA certificate\n   - The token uses the WarnOnlyBoundTokenExpirationSeconds expiration setting\n\nThe admission controller is registered with the name \"ServiceAccount\" and processes both Pod CREATE and UPDATE operations.\n\n## Token Controller (Secret Creation)\nThe token controller at `pkg/controller/serviceaccount/tokens_controller.go` creates and manages the actual token secrets:\n\n1. **TokensController** is initialized by `NewTokensController()` (line 74) with:\n   - A TokenGenerator for creating signed JWT tokens\n   - Service account and secret informers for tracking changes\n   - Work queues for asynchronous processing\n\n2. The controller watches ServiceAccount objects and creates corresponding SecretTypeServiceAccountToken secrets containing:\n   - The token data (signed JWT)\n   - Annotations linking to the ServiceAccount (name and UID)\n   - The root CA certificate\n\n## Token Generation\nThe `pkg/serviceaccount/jwt.go` file provides:\n\n1. **JWTTokenGenerator()** (line 61): Creates a TokenGenerator that signs tokens using RSA or ECDSA private keys\n2. **TokenGenerator interface**: Defines the contract for token generation\n\n## Service Account Token Controller Setup\nThe `cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/service_accounts.go` orchestrates initialization:\n\n1. **newServiceAccountTokenControllerDescriptor()** (line 33): Creates a ControllerDescriptor marked as requiring special handling (started first before other controllers)\n\n2. **newServiceAccountTokenController()** (line 45): Initializes the TokensController by:\n   - Reading the service account signing private key file\n   - Reading the root CA certificate\n   - Creating a JWTTokenGenerator\n   - Instantiating the TokensController with these components\n\n## Pod Spec Validation\nThe AutomountServiceAccountToken field is defined in:\n- `pkg/apis/core/types.go` (PodSpec at line 3734, ServiceAccount at line 5326)\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/api/core/v1/types.go` (the v1 API version definitions)\n\nThis boolean field (when set) overrides the default behavior and allows users to explicitly disable token mounting for specific pods or service accounts.\n\n## Supporting Components\n1. **Token Request Storage** (`pkg/registry/core/serviceaccount/storage/token.go`): Handles the TokenRequest API for pod-bound token requests\n2. **Service Account Claims** (`pkg/serviceaccount/claims.go`): Validates JWT claims and pod/service account associations\n3. **Kubelet Token Manager** (`pkg/kubelet/token/token_manager.go`): Manages token refresh and caching at the node level\n4. **Legacy Token Cleaner** (`pkg/controller/serviceaccount/legacy_serviceaccount_token_cleaner.go`): Cleans up old-style token secrets when bound tokens are used\n5. **Pod Utilities** (`pkg/api/pod/util.go`): Contains helper functions for analyzing projected volumes and token paths\n\nThe complete flow is: Pod is created → ServiceAccount admission controller checks AutomountServiceAccountToken → Injects projected volume → Token controller creates/updates the secret with signed JWT → Kubelet mounts the secret at the standard path."
}

